##  Beagle use

Beagle basic verb vocabulary is HTTP-based and all addressing is URI-based.

  - `get <uri>` is clone/pull/checkout;
  - `post <uri>` is commit/fast-forward/push;
  - `patch <uri>` is merge/rebase/etc;
  - `put <file>` is stage (also set ref);
  - `delete <file>` is stage deletion (also drop ref);

Most of the time you would probably use the TUI.
Start with `be status` or `be work` for an overview.
All Beagle commands start the pager/TUI by default.
`:` is the command mode (e.g. `:status<Enter>`).
`q` or `:quit<Enter>` is quit.

##  Beagle features

 1. This implementation is [TUI-centric][s], any command opens a pager.
 2. The TUI is browser-like, all things that can be clickable are clickable.
 3. Both external (e.g. GitHub) and internal (e.g. worktrees) addressing is URI-based.
 4. Beagle expects [*lots* of worktrees][w1] and many agentic sessions to run in parallel.
 5. Worktrees get organized into a parent-fork tree, just to keep track of them.

##  Build and Installation

The only dependency is [JAB][j] the minimalistic JavaScript runtime with revision control specific bindings and APIs.
Build it or download it from GitHub, install it in your `$PATH`. 
You may also want to install a symlink, like `be -> jab`.
JAB picks the sources from `jsrc/` dirs in `$PWD` and up the parent chain (not `node_modules`).
For example `jab hello` would look for `.../jsrc/views/hello/hello.js` or `.../jsrc/verbs/hello/hello.js`.
See the `jsrc` self-link in this repo; it lets a Beagle repo revision-control itself.
A bad change may have difficulty being committed in the first place :)

##  Customization and Speciation

Any user-facing behavior is implemented in JavaScript and customizable.
Users are 100% expected to develop their custom verb/view sets. 
Any established workflow should be taken from LLM's probabilistic hands and [automated][a].
Just put your `jsrc/` on a different level than Beagle's if you want to build on top of it.
Creating your own set of commands from scratch is also OK, it just takes longer.
All the revision-control heavy-lifting, source code tokenization and suchlike is all done by [libdog][d] through JAB bindings.

